SIMPLE: slumber
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slumber
<hw>Slum"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slumbered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Slumbering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>slombren</ets>, <ets>slumberen</ets>, <ets>slumeren</ets>, AS.
<ets>slumerian</ets>, fr. <ets>sluma</ets> slumber; akin to D.
<ets>sluimeren</ets> to slumber, MHG. <ets>slummern</ets>,
<ets>slumen</ets>, G. <ets>schlummern</ets>, Dan. <ets>slumre</ets>, Sw.
<ets>slumra</ets>, Goth. <ets>slawan</ets> to be silent.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To sleep; especially, to sleep lightly; to doze.</def>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that keepeth Israel shall neither <qex>slumber</qex> nor
sleep.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxxi. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be in a state of negligence, sloth, supineness,
or inactivity.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Why <xex>slumbers</xex> Pope?⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slumber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slumber
<hw>Slum"ber</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay to
sleep.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stun; to stupefy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slumber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slumber
<hw>Slum"ber</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Sleep; especially, light sleep;
sleep that is not deep or sound; repose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He at last fell into a <qex>slumber</qex>, and thence into a fast
sleep, which detained him in that place until it was almost night.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fast asleep? It is no matter;⟦br⟧
Enjoy the honey-heavy dew of <qex>slumber</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rest to my soul, and <qex>slumber</qex> to my eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slumberer</ent>⟦br⟧
